args: You are so focused on Zace, you left\nyourself wide open. HAAAAH!
My apologies, Zace. That happened\nbecause I was unable to finish it off.
I am unhurt. However, I can't say the same\nfor this...
Oh no... Does that mean the sound I heard\nearlier was the breaking of one of the\nbones you carry?
Still, better a carried bone than one\nof our own, I suppose.
Man, Zace is lookin' even gloomier than\nusual.
I fear this is my fault.
And while I'm not good at brightening\npeople's spirits when they're down,\nI have to at least make the attempt.
The bone that got broken, I mean.\nEr...was it valuable?
Valuable? No, it was a rather common\nexample that can be found in any human.
It belonged to my mother—or so I was\ntold. She died when I was a baby.
My father pitied me for growing up without\nher, and so left me that to remember her.
Perhaps because I grew up hearing that\nstory, I started to feel as though there was\na comforting warmth within it.
That may have been what led to me\nliking bones as much as I do.
I had no idea it was so precious!
Don't trouble yourself over it, Elisanne.\nIt was due to my own inattention.
Yet it was so important to you...
It's all right. What I wanted more than\none of my mother's bones...
I'm happy it was used to save the life of\na living person, even if it was destroyed in\nthe process.
In that case, I am going to make you a\npromise, Zace.
You saved me, and because of that,\nI swear not to let my life go to waste.
I would like that very much.
Still, I can't JUST do that. I must thank\nyou in a more traditional way as well.
Did you have something in mind?
Well, if you were ever to die, Elisanne...\nMight I have your bones?
How did I know we might end up here?\nBut after I die, my bones can–
I would LIKE to do so, but alas,\nI am a Paladyn.
My body must be offered up to the Church.\nI'm very sorry, but my bones belong to\nthat institution alone.
I...I see. I suppose that is that.
If you think of anything else you might\nwant as thanks, please let me know.
What she says makes sense. Ah, I suppose\nI've no choice but to abandon my pursuit\nof her bones.
Wait a moment. Humans have two hundred\nand six bones in their body...
Surely even the Ilian Church would not\nneed QUITE so many...
What about just one bone?!\nJust one would be wonderful!
